reviews.review_text:
The template for the rest of the band’s years. 76 is when Garcia started to really push how slow you can play a tune and still make it sound like you aren’t falling asleep 😴 He did it in the JGB around this time  and was doing it in the Dead too, with two drummers. There is certainly a challenge to playing that slow in a band that size and not having everything fall apart. Jerry Garcia was a master at that.
People talk about Dead and Co.’s slow tempos but remember, the Grateful Dead did it first.
Jerry always liked the ballads and most of his original tunes are slower or more laid back, when compared to Bob’s  but listen to “Wharf Rat” here, after one of the more listless “Dancin’ in the Streets” of this tour and you’ll get what I mean. At times he almost sounds like he’s nodding off in mid-verse. Maybe he was. As Garcia went it seems so did the Grateful Dead. Leader or not, Jerry was steering the ship for a while and if he was having an off night then so was the rest of the band.
I’m not sure what happened after “Help/Slip/Frank’s” because everything before that including the first set, is solid. His lines are melodic and articulate, his singing strong. They seem to pick it back it up however at the end of set two finishing somewhat strong.
The more I listen to 1976 Dead, the more it becomes apparent to me that the new drugs of choice around this time were doing more harm than good for the music and this would continue until the end. This can’t be denied.
The shows of this year and every year after until the end in 1995, are either really great or just okay. Compare this to all the years before the hiatus where even the mediocre/run-of- the mill shows of 70-74 were way better than some of the ones of 1976 and beyond. 
Someone who reviewed another show from 1976 commented on the “laziness” of some of the performances. That is a word for it. Another word for it would be opiates.

THIS SHOW IS SICK and I mean sick in a confident, jazzy sorta way - not a DOPEsick manner suggested by a previous reviewer, Opiates with their horrors end poorly for most who form relationships with them. That being said, like most long term relationships, one with opiates has incredible highs and lows. It's just wrongheaded to go searching for heroin nod outs in this era - it's in another times forgotten space. The music of the Grateful Dead benefitted from WHATEREVER the fuck the band individually or collectively ingested. I mean COME ON '76 on well into 1978 produced as much fabled, mind melting performances as any vaulted period. If you're in the mood for some real deal mid 70's spun magic from a cool and confident Grateful Dead, then absolutely give this show a whirl. Go peck around somewhere bouts 1994/95 if you're morbidly obsessed with the sorrowful end days of a relationship we all wish had been merely an affair. Otherwise feel liberated to enjoy the hell out of the band strutting their stuff.
